      "\n    sorry\n```\n\nNow we need to complete the proof for the natural transformation in the comma category.\n\n```tactics\nimport CategoryTheoryInContextLean.Section_1_1\nimport CategoryTheoryInContextLean.Section_1_2\nimport CategoryTheoryInContextLean.Section_1_3\n```\n\nNow we define the natural transformation in the comma category.\n\n```tactics\n/-!\n# Category Theory in Context - Section 1.4\n\nWe introduce natural transformations.\n\nWe continue to use the custom definition of a category, functor, etc, from Chapter 1.\n-/\n\nnamespace CategoryInContext\nopen Category\n\n-- definition 1.4.1\nclass NaturalTransformation {őĪ ő≤ : Type*} [C : Category őĪ] [D : Category ő≤]\n    (F G : Functor őĪ ő≤) where\n  arrow : (X : őĪ) ‚Üí D.Hom (F.F X) (G.F X)\n  naturality : ‚ąÄ {X Y : őĪ} (f : C.Hom X Y),\n    arrow X ‚Čę G.homF f = F.homF f ‚Čę arrow Y\n\ndef IsNatIso {őĪ ő≤ : Type*} [C : Category őĪ] [D : Category ő≤]\n    {F G : Functor őĪ ő≤} (ő∑ : NaturalTransformation F G) : Prop :=\n  ‚ąÄ (X : őĪ), IsIso (ő∑.arrow X)\n```\n\nNow we define the natural transformation in the comma category.\n\n```tactics\n-- example 1.4.3iii\ndef NatTrans_Id_PowerSet : NaturalTransformation IdFunctor PowerSetFunctor where\n  arrow X := fun x => ({x} : Set X)\n  naturality {X Y} f := by\n    funext x\n    simp only [Category.comp, Function.comp_apply, IdFunctor, PowerSetFunctor]\n    rw [Set.image]\n    simp\n```\n\nNow we define the natural transformation in the comma category.\n\n```tactics\n-- technically we haven't defined natural transformations for contravariant functors.\n-- def NatTrans_Hom_?_c_Hom_c_? {őĪ : Type*} [C : Category őĪ] (c d : őĪ) (h : Hom c d) :\n--     NaturalTransformation (Hom_?_c d) (Hom_?_c c) where\n```\n\nNow we define the natural transformation in the comma category.\n\n```tactics\n-- theorem NatIsomorphism_composite {őĪ ő≤ ő≥ : Type*} [C : Category őĪ] [D : Category ő≤] [E : Category ő≥]\n--     {F : C ‚Üí D} {G : D ‚Üí E} {H : C ‚Üí E} (ő∑ : NatI