- `B` should be `fun X ‚Ü¶ h_X` (the map we need to compose with)

Then the left side would be `comp (fun X ‚Ü¶ h_X.symm) (fun X ‚Ü¶ h_X)`.
This would be `(fun X ‚Ü¶ h_X.symm) ‚ąė (fun X ‚Ü¶ h_X)`.
For an input `X`, this would be `h_X.symm (h_X X)`.
`h_X X` is the map `F(d) ‚Üí G(e)`.
`h_X.symm` is the map `G(e) ‚Üí F(d)`.
So `h_X.symm (h_X X)` is `G(e) ‚Üí F(d)` applied to `F(d) ‚Üí G(e)`.
This results in `F(d) ‚Üí F(d)`, which is `id`.

The right side would be `comp (fun X ‚Ü¶ h_X) (fun X ‚Ü¶ h_X.symm)`.
This would be `(fun X ‚Ü¶ h_X) ‚ąė (fun X ‚Ü¶ h_X.symm)`.
For an input `X`, this would be `h_X (h_X.symm X)`.
`h_X.symm X` is the map `G(e) ‚Üí F(d)`.
`h_X` is the map `F(d) ‚Üí G(e)`.
So `h_X (h_X.symm X)` is `F(d) ‚Üí G(e)` applied to `G(e) ‚Üí F(d)`.
This results in `G(e) ‚Üí G(e)`, which is `id`.

So the equality `comp (fun X ‚Ü¶ h_X.symm) (fun X ‚Ü¶ h_X) = comp (fun X ‚Ü¶ h_X) (fun X ‚Ü¶ h_X.symm)` is indeed true, as both sides reduce to `id`.

